04319nam a22006615i 9780271075556DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211992pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710755567 a10.1515/97802710755562doi  a(DE-B1597)584170  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPQ2344.Z5bS53 1993 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a841/.82201 aShaw, Mary Lewis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerformance in the Texts of Mallarmé :bThe Passage from Art to Ritual /cMary Lewis Shaw. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Performance as Ritual -- t2. Music: "Le dernier et plénier culte humain" -- t3. Dance: "Rite . . . énoncé de l'Idée" -- t4. Theater: "Le vrai culte moderne" -- t5. Opera: "Le Monstre-Qui-ne-peut-Être" -- t6. "La fausse entrée des sorcières dans Macbeth" -- t7. Hérodiade -- t8. L'après-midi d'un faune -- t9. lgitur -- t10. Un coup de dés -- t11. Le Livre -- t12. Avant-Garde Performance -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerformance in the Texts of Mallarmé offers a new theory of performance in the poetic and critical texts of Stephane Mallarmé, a theory challenging the prevailing interpretation of his work as epitomizing literary purism and art for art's sake.Following an analytical presentation of the concepts of ritual and performance generally applied, Mary Shaw shows that Mallarmé perceived music, dance, and theater as ideal languages of the body and therefore as ideal forms of ritual through which to supplement and celebrate poetic texts. She focuses on previously unexplored references to supplementary, extratextual performances in four of Mallarmé's major poetic texts-Herodiade, L'après-midi d'un faune, Igitur, and Un coup de des-revealing the consistent formal expression of his original conception of literature's relationship to the performing arts.Shaw then discusses Mallarmé's monumental project, Le Livre, a metaphysical book designed to be performed in a series of ritual celebrations. She analyzes and describes the intrinsic structure and contents of this unfinished work as the fullest realization of the text-performance relationship elaborated throughout Mallarmé's corpus. Shaw offers Le Livre as a prototype of avant-garde performance, drawing important parallels between Mallarmé's literary experimentation and crucial developments in twentieth-century arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics). 0aPerforming arts in literature. 0aRitual in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271075556zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271075556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271075556.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK